\begin_layout Standard
For many combinatorial applications, an informal understanding of probability
 theory (often considering only discrete spaces) will suffice.
 However, in this thesis a rigorous foundation in probability theory will
 be useful.
 This chapter will assume knowledge of basic measure theory; see, for example,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rud66"

\end_inset

.
 However, where possible, we will note any simplifications that arise from
 assuming discreteness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No knowledge of probability theory is assumed; the first few subsections
 will briefly review the foundations of probability.
 The reader may nevertheless want to refer to a probability theory book
 such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kal02"

\end_inset

 for some additional detail and further reading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Probability Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\emph on
probability space
\emph default
 is a measure space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA,\Pr\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\Om\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
, and denote the set of all probability measures on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(\Om\right)$
\end_inset

 if there is no ambiguity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:discrete-space"

\end_inset

For our purposes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om$
\end_inset

 will often be countable, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\cA$
\end_inset

 as the power set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined by the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\om\right):=\Pr\left(\left\{ \om\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\om\in\Om$
\end_inset

.
 We will discuss specific probability spaces on sets of combinatorial objects
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:random-structures"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An 
\emph on
event
\emph default
 in a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA,\Pr\right)$
\end_inset

 is a measurable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\in\cA$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

, we interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\A\right)$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 occurs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Events will usually be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\A=\left\{ \om\in\Om:\, P\left(\om\right)\mbox{ holds}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\om\right)$
\end_inset

 is some property of an object 
\begin_inset Formula $\om$
\end_inset

.
 For clarity, we often abuse notation slightly and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(P\mbox{ holds}\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\left\{ \om\in\Om:\, P\left(\om\right)\mbox{ holds}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random Elements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\emph on
random element
\emph default
 is a measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\X:\left(\Om_{1},\cA_{1}\right)\to\left(\Om_{2},\cA_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 between measurable spaces.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om_{2}=\RR^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\NN$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\cA_{2}$
\end_inset

 the Borel 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\left(\RR^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{n}$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
random vector
\emph default
.
 A one-dimensional random vector is a 
\emph on
random variable
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om_{2}$
\end_inset

 is countable then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
discrete
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Especially in combinatorial spaces, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Om_{1}$
\end_inset

 is often countable.
 In this case, any function from a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om_{1},2^{\Om_{1}},\Pr\right)$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To interpret a random variable, we need a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 on the underlying measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om_{1},\cA_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 (often, this will be implicit).
 Then, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\X\in\A\right)=\Pr\left(\left\{ \om\in\Om_{1}:\X\left(\om\right)\in\A\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 takes a value in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

.
 Often, we will only be interested in such probabilities: that is, we do
 not care about the realization of a random variable as a function on an
 underlying probability space.
 This motivates the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is a random element which takes values in the measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
distribution
\emph default
 (or 
\emph on
law
\emph default
) 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 with respect to an underlying probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is the pushforward measure with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

.
 That is, it is a probability measure defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}\left(\A\right)=\Pr\left(\X^{-1}\left(\A\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\subseteq\cA$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we occasionally use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X}:=\L{\X}$
\end_inset

 for ease of reading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth noting that in fact any probability measure is the distribution
 of some random element, so we can define a probability distribution abstractly
 and then assert the existence of a random variable with that distribution.
 To see this, note that given a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{}\in\P\left(\Om\right)$
\end_inset

, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X=\id_{\Om}$
\end_inset

 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}=\L{}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the underlying probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\X\in\L{}$
\end_inset

 to indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 has distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The 
\emph on
normal distribution
\emph default
 with parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\N_{\mu,\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\N_{\mu,\sigma}\left(B\right)=\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{B}e^{-\frac{\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}\d x
\]

\end_inset

for any Borel set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}\left(\RR\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We can use the Gaussian integral to show that this is indeed a probability
 measure, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\N_{\mu,\sigma}\left(\RR\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The normal distribution will be of particular importance in this thesis,
 so we make some remarks.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\X\in\N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\X=\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Var\X=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (this second fact can be established using integration by parts and the
 Gaussian integral).
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\X\in\N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\X-\mu}{\sigma}\in\N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 So, we will sometimes only consider the 
\emph on
standard normal
\emph default
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\N\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

, with the understanding that it is very easy to transfer results to other
 normal distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The 
\emph on
Poisson distribution
\emph default
 with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Po\left(\lambda\right)=\Po_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

; this is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Po_{\lambda}\left(k\right)=\frac{\lambda^{k}e^{-\lambda}}{k!}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\NN$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:discrete-space"

\end_inset

).
 The Taylor expansion of the exponential can be used to show that this indeed
 defines a probability measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is in general a little tricky to define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the set of values a random element can take
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but this is straightforward in the discrete case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\emph on
support
\emph default
 of a discrete random element 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\supp\left(\X\right)=\left\{ k\in\Om:\Pr\left(\X=k\right)>0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dependence and Coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\X'$
\end_inset

 are random elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om_{1},\cA_{1},\Pr\right)\to\left(\Om_{2},\cA_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\X'$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
independent
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left(\X\in\A_{2}\right)\Pr\left(\X'\in\A_{2}\right)=\Pr\left(\X\in\A_{2}\mbox{ and }\X'\in\A_{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{2}\in\cA_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{1},\A_{1}'\in\cA$
\end_inset

 then we analogously say 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{1}'$
\end_inset

 are independent if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left(\A_{1}\right)\Pr\left(\A_{1}'\right)=\Pr\left(\A_{1}\cap\A_{1}'\right).
\]

\end_inset

We can similarly say an event is independent of a random element.
 If two objects are not independent, then we say they are 
\emph on
dependent
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, two objects are dependent if information about one object can
 give information about the other.
 For example, we might be interested in the probability of an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

, under the assumption that the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A'$
\end_inset

 occurs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\emph on
conditional probability
\emph default
 of an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

, given an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A'$
\end_inset

 which has nonzero probability, is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\A|\A'\right)=\Pr\left(\A\cap\A'\right)/\Pr\left(\A'\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\A|\A'\right)=\Pr\left(\A\right)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\A'$
\end_inset

 are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also condition random elements on an event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X:\left(\Om_{1},\cA_{1},\Pr\right)\to\left(\Om_{2},\cA_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a random element, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{1}\in\cA_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an event with nonzero probability.
 Then the 
\emph on
distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 conditioned on 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{1}$
\end_inset


\emph default
 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X|\A_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X|\A_{1}}\left(\A_{2}\right)=\Pr\left(\X\in\A_{2}|\A_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{2}\in\cA_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a finite collection of measure spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om_{1},\cA_{1},\m_{1}\right),\dots,\left(\Om_{n},\cA_{n},\m_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, recall the construction of the product measure space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA,\m\right):=\left(\prod_{i=1}^{n}\Om_{i},\,\bigotimes_{i=1}^{n}\cA_{i},\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\m_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Chapter~8"
key "Rud66"

\end_inset

).
 If a random element takes values in a product space then each component
 is measurable, and conversely if the components of a random tuple are measurabl
e then that tuple is measurable in the product space.
 So, we can make the following definitions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given random elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\X_{1},\dots,\X_{n}$
\end_inset

 on the same underlying probability space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{1},\dots,\X_{n}}:=\Lb{\left(\X_{1},\dots,\X_{n}\right)}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
joint distribution
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X_{1},\dots,\X_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, given a random tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X_{1},\dots,\X_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{\i}}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
marginal distribution
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have two distributions of random elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Coupling
\emph default
 is the technique of constructing a random ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X_{1},\X_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 which realizes the given distributions as marginal distributions.
 Usually this is done by specifying the joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{1},\X_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is that coupling creates a particular kind of dependence between
 
\begin_inset Formula $\X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\X_{2}$
\end_inset

 that allows us to compare the two distributions.
 Often, we are able to make conclusions about the distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X_{\i}}$
\end_inset

 which are independent of their specific realizations as random elements
 in the coupling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\L X\left(0\right)=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\L X\left(1\right)=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\L Y\left(0\right)=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\L Y\left(1\right)=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can couple 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 into a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{X,Y}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{2}$
\end_inset

, defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\L{X,Y}\left(0,0\right)=\frac{1}{3},\quad\L{X,Y}\left(0,1\right)=\frac{1}{6},\quad\L{X,Y}\left(1,0\right)=0,\quad\L{X,Y}\left(1,1\right)=\frac{1}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

In this coupling, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X=0$
\end_inset

, which allows us to make the observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\L X\left(0\right)\ge\L Y\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, this was already obvious, but hopefully this example illustrates
 the principle that coupling random variables allows us to make direct compariso
ns between their distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expected Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\emph on
expected value
\emph default
 of a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 (or its distribution) is the measure-theoretic integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\X=\int x\d\L{\X}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It can be intuitively understood as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 value that random variable takes.
 The 
\emph on
variance
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is a measure of how much variation there is from the expected value; it
 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Var\X=\E\left(\X-\E\X\right)^{2}=\E\X^{2}-\left(\E\X\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:discrete-expectation"

\end_inset

For a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 that takes integer values, our definition of expected value is equivalent
 to the well-known formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\X=\sum_{x\in\ZZ}x\,\Pr\left(\X=x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:indicator-expectation"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is a random variable that can be interpreted as counting the number of
 objects that satisfy some property, then we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 as a sum of indicator variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\i}\one_{\A_{\i}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\A_{\i}$
\end_inset

 is the event that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\i$
\end_inset

th object satisfies our property.
 Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\E$
\end_inset

 is linear, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\X=\sum_{\i}\E\one_{\A_{\i}}=\sum_{\i}\Pr\A_{\i}$
\end_inset

.
 So, in order to compute the expectation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 we just need to compute the probability that each object satisfies our
 required property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we fix a particular underlying probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA,\Pr\right)$
\end_inset

, we can also equivalently view expectation as a linear functional on the
 space of real integrable functions (i.e.
 random variables).
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\E:L^{1}\left(\Om,\Pr\right)\to\RR$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\E f=\int f\left(\om\right)\d\Pr$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes we will define a new probability measure on an existing measurable
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{\Pr'}$
\end_inset

 to indicate expectation with respect to the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr'$
\end_inset

, to avoid ambiguity.
 We can also define the expectation functional of a random variable: 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{\X}:=\E_{\Lb{\X}}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{\X}f=\E f\left(\X\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f:L^{1}\left(\RR,\Lb{\X}\right)$
\end_inset

.
