\begin_layout Standard
The typical application of a switching is to estimate the relative sizes
 of some subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om$
\end_inset

, by analysing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of switchings between the subsets.
 The switching is generally designed in such a way that this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is maximized in a certain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HM10"

\end_inset

 for a discussion of switchings in generality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our case, define 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-regular graphs with exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 cycles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 The switching in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:cycle-switching"

\end_inset

 has been chosen so that it attempts to remove exactly one short cycle in
 a graph, so that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 is large.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Section~3"
key "MWW04"

\end_inset

, an estimate was obtained for the average number of ways 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

switch into 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 (that is, the average number of 
\begin_inset Formula $G'\in S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 which satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $G\rightsquigarrow G'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 ranges over 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, an estimate was obtained for the average number of ways 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

switch from 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 (that is, the average number of 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $G\rightsquigarrow G'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 ranges over 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)F\left(k\right)=S\left(k-1\right)B\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 is the number of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(G,G'\right)\in S\left(k\right)\times S\left(k-1\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G\rightsquigarrow G'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimates on 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 can be combined for an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pr\left(\X_{\ell,n}^{\left(d\right)}=k\right)}{\Pr\left(\X_{\ell,n}^{\left(d\right)}=0\right)}=\frac{S\left(k\right)}{S\left(0\right)}=\frac{B\left(0\right)\dots B\left(k-1\right)}{F\left(1\right)\dots F\left(k\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which can then be used to estimate the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X_{\ell,n}^{\left(d\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stein's Method and Switchings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\fG}{\mathfrak{G}}
{\boldsymbol{\mathfrak{G}}}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obvious parallels can be drawn between the application of switchings in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MWW04"

\end_inset

 and the application of Stein's method in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "example:poisson-connecting-operator"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

probability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that the (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) switching 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

destroys a cycle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

probability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 switching 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

creates a cycle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, both given that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 existing cycles.
 These are analogous to the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\X_{2}=\X_{1}-1|\X_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\X_{2}=\X_{1}+1|\X_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 that were estimated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "example:poisson-connecting-operator"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea, then, is to use a switching to define a suitable exchangeable
 pair, and to adapt the switching estimates for use with Stein's method.
 There are two main advantages of this approach over a bare-hands switching
 argument.
 First, a regular switching argument requires individual estimates of each
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

, but Stein's method allows us to estimate the relevant probabilities only
 in expectation (effectively, we are only estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[\lambda-cB\left(\X\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[\X-cF\left(\X\right)\right]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the parameter of the approximating Poisson distribution).
 Second, our final estimate is likely to be sharper when using Stein's method,
 because we can take advantage of the sophisticated estimates developed
 for Stein's method rather than using elementary ad-hoc estimates.
 In particular, the improvement in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:short-cycles-variable"

\end_inset

 over the natural bound in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MWW04"

\end_inset

 is due to the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EXT0-immigration-death-bound"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is that a switching 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightsquigarrow$
\end_inset

 defines a graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\fG$
\end_inset

 with an edge for every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(G,G'\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G\rightsquigarrow G'$
\end_inset

, whose edges we can weight if desired.
 Loops are then added as necessary to so that each vertex has the same weight
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:graph-to-markov"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\fG$
\end_inset

 induces a reversible Markov chain with uniform stationary distribution
 (in our case 
\begin_inset Formula $\rG nd)$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to an exchangeable pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}=\left(G_{1},G_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 with margins 
\begin_inset Formula $\rG nd$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:underlying-pair"

\end_inset

, this provides us an exchangeable pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\bX=\left(\X_{1},\X_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 with margins 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}$
\end_inset

, which we use to apply Stein's method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give a very simplified sketch of the proof of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:short-cycles-variable"

\end_inset

.
 We use the switching in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:cycle-switching"

\end_inset

.
 Assign all edges in 
\begin_inset Formula $\fG$
\end_inset

 a weight of 1, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\X=\X_{\ell,n}^{\left(d\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}\left(G\right)$
\end_inset

 be the number of ways to switch out of a graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by destroying an 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq K_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\falling n{\ell}/\left(2\ell\right)$
\end_inset

 cycles in the complete graph 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vertices, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\E\left|\X_{1}-c\Pr\left(\X_{2}=\X_{1}+1|\X_{1}\right)\right| & \le\E\left|\sum_{C\in K_{n}}\one_{C\subseteq G_{1}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}\sum_{C\in K_{n}}F_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|\nonumber \\
 & \le\frac{\falling n{\ell}}{2\ell}\E\left|\one_{C\subseteq G_{1}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}F_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|.\label{eq:short-cycles-increment-bound}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

Similarly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{C}\left(G\right)$
\end_inset

 be the number of ways to switch into 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by destroying 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\E\left|\frac{\left(d-1\right)^{\ell}}{2\ell}-c\Pr\left(\X_{2}=\X_{1}+1|\X_{1}\right)\right|\le\frac{\falling n{\ell}}{2\ell}\,\E\left|\frac{\left(d-1\right)^{\ell}}{\falling n{\ell}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}B_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|.\label{eq:short-cycles-decrement-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, if 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{C}\left(G\right)\approx\falling n{\ell}\, d^{\ell}/2^{\ell}.\label{eq:FC-approximate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To see this, note that a forwards switching is determined by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{\i}\right\} _{\i}$
\end_inset

 and a neighbour 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\i}$
\end_inset

 for each.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, there are about 
\begin_inset Formula $\falling n{\ell}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{\i}\right\} _{\i}$
\end_inset

, and each 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\i}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 neighbors (for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 these are unlikely to interfere with each other).
 Because each 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\i}$
\end_inset

 can be interchanged, resulting in the same switching, we then need to divide
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{C}\left(G\right)\approx{d \choose 2}^{\ell},\label{eq:BC-approximate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because a switching that destroyed 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to create 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 can be identified with a path 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\i}v_{\i}w_{\i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\i}\in C$
\end_inset

, and there are about 
\begin_inset Formula ${d \choose 2}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose these paths.
 With these estimates in mind, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\Delta2^{\ell}/\left(\falling n{\ell}d^{\ell}\right)$
\end_inset

, so that both of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E\left|\one_{C\subseteq G_{1}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}F_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|,\quad\E\left|\frac{\left(d-1\right)^{\ell}}{\falling n{\ell}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}B_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|
\]

\end_inset

are small.
 The arguments needed to actually obtain bounds on these expectations can
 be mostly adapted from corresponding arguments in the bare-hands application
 of switchings in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MWW04"

\end_inset

, which we will now sketch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the argument used to establish 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FC-approximate"

\end_inset

, we know that a switching that destroys a cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is determined by a choice of a set of edges 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{\i}u_{\i}\right\} _{\i=1}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 To estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[F_{C}\left(G\right)\right]$
\end_inset

, we need a lower bound (in expectation) of the number of such choices that
 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

legal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as per 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:cycle-switching"

\end_inset

 (that is, the relevant vertices are distinct and no extraneous cycles are
 created or destroyed).
 A choice will certainly be legal if we require that each of the edges 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\i}u_{\i}$
\end_inset

 are a certain minimum distance (say 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

) away from each other and of the cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, and we also require that none of the edges 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\i}u_{\i}$
\end_inset

 are part of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

short cycle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (a cycle with length less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

).
 The number of vertices with distance less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 from a particular vertex is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\ell}$
\end_inset

, which is a vanishingly small proportion of the vertices of a large graph.
 Due to this and the fact that short cycles are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rare
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in expectation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:short-cycles-are-rare"

\end_inset

), it can be shown combinatorially that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E\left|\one_{C\subseteq G_{1}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}F_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|=O\left(\frac{\ell\left(d-1\right)^{2\ell-1}}{n^{\ell+1}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

We similarly need to investigate the sharpness of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BC-approximate"

\end_inset

 by bounding the number of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

legal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 choices of sets of paths 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u_{\i}v_{\i}w_{\i}\right\} _{\i=1}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 For this, we restrict our attention to such choices where no edge 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\i}u_{\i}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\i}w_{\i}$
\end_inset

 is contained in a short cycle, and the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\i}v_{\i}w_{\i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\ii}v_{\ii}w_{\ii}$
\end_inset

 is exactly the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ii}$
\end_inset

.
 We can then obtain a similar bound
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E\left|\frac{\left(d-1\right)^{\ell}}{\falling n{\ell}}-\frac{c}{\Delta}B_{C}\left(G_{1}\right)\right|=O\left(\frac{\ell\left(d-1\right)^{2\ell-1}}{n^{\ell+1}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Combining these estimates with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:short-cycles-increment-bound"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:short-cycles-decrement-bound"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EXT0-immigration-death-bound"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:stein-distance-transform"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:short-cycles-variable"

\end_inset

 can be shown to follow.
\end_layout

