\begin_layout Standard
There are many aspects of Stein's method that we were unable to cover in
 this thesis.
 We have discussed approximation only with the Poisson and normal distributions,
 but Stein's method has been applied in much more generality.
 The method has been applied for other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distributions such as the exponential, geometric and semicircle distributions
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ros11,FL14"

\end_inset

).
 More interestingly, Stein's method has been used to make approximations
 to application-specific distributions (see, for example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BCX07"

\end_inset

).
 This is done using general characterizing operator constructions such as
 the exchangeable pairs approach (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:characterizing-from-exchangeable-pair"

\end_inset

), and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generator approach
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BC05"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, while we were able to discuss the method of size-bias coupling (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:size-bias-coupling"

\end_inset

), there are several other distributional transformations that can be used
 to control the expectations produced by the Stein transformation.
 The most notable of these is zero-biasing (see, for example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Section~2.3.3"
key "CGS10"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have only discussed Stein's method as a tool for bounding the distance
 between distributions, but the method can be applied to prove other types
 of results, including, for example, concentration inequalities (see, for
 example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Section~7"
key "Ros11"

\end_inset

).
 The method has even been used for totally non-probabilistic results, such
 as the asymptotic enumeration of Latin rectangles (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Section~XI"
key "Ste86"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, it is worth remarking that Stein's method is currently an active
 area of research, particularly in the fields of stochastic processes and
 random matrix theory.
 In fact, several interesting papers appeared on the arXiv too recently
 for me to be able to discuss them in the body of this thesis.
 The reader may be interested in a very recent survey paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
